North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions strengthened its distrust of the United States and that the country would in no way agree to unilaterally drop its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual General Assembly that North Korea has carried out “significant goodwill measures” over the past year, for example by halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We have not seen any similar response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we have no trust in our national security, and under such circumstances, under no circumstances will we unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints of Washington’s opposition to a gradual nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea is rewarded for gradual disarmament, but his statement was significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament completely, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump issued in Singapore on June 12, at the very first meeting between a sitting president of the United States and a North Korean leader, where Kim promised to work towards “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first drop its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to reduce stringent international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘nuclear disarmament first,’ lifting pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even opposes the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can push us to our knees is a dream for people who don’t know anything about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions create further distrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump, which the US leader stressed in front of the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae over the past five months, adding: “If the other party in this disarmament case was South Korea, rather than the United States, the Korean Peninsula nuclear disarmament would not have been as tightly locked as it is.”
