Students at Harvard take courses in getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is designed to help students get more sleep by tackling the growing ukulele of poking through the night with caffeinated beverages as fuel.
One academic found that students at the world’s best universities often had no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He started the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the lecture, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why hasn’t anyone said this before?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which starts this year, explains to students how important good sleep habits are to be able to perform academically and athletically, and for the general condition.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to start the course after seeing students suffer from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts for one hour, has a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is a picture of a room in a dormitory, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books and learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important it is to a sleep routine.
In another part, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons makes participants think about their own daily routine.
“We are aware that this is not going to change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know about this, just as you have the right to know about the risks of smoking,” said Professor Czeisler.
There is still some pride in being able to crawl all night, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students led to sleep deprivation being an increasing problem.
Enough and good sleep should be students’ “secret weapons” against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even as a means against weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in hunger mode, leading to constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course. He took one of the professor’s classes last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said the course inspired him to work for a course that was available for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all master’s students to take a similar study program before they are enrolled at the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students put on an alarm for when to lie down as well as for when to stand up, and that they should be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic displays and LED lights. This type of light can disrupt the 24-hour rhythm and lead to sleep difficulties.
