And now a page from the “Sunday Morning” almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago, was the day when the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm “Hans” Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, a discovery that led to the apparatus we now know as the Geiger Plate.
The violin has been an important part of science ever since, and also became a part of popular culture through the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: “What the hell is that?”
Rogers: “It’s a geiger counter. It finds radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you touch these headphones, you can hear the effect of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals.”
Evans: “I have to say it makes sound now!”
