The National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Fleas
New research conducted at a farm in the Scottish Highlands will reveal how bats use the landscape in the hunt for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and help design future conservation measures.
The study by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brown longtails and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at important locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analyses of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bats and which species do what.
Then a habitat map and a report will be prepared to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will be part of the decision on what measures should be taken, such as the establishment of pastures and how best to care for the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction work affecting breeding grounds and habitat constraints.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, the same with fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials, as well as attacks from household cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for the ears than the eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road when flying.
The NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten skilled experts who regularly carry out surveys, mapping of nesting sites and sometimes rescue work.
The organization has also established Scotland's first and only own bat reserve at Thrave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Thrave we have a perfect area for bats,” he says.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of mapping the bats before maintenance is carried out on a property since accidental destruction of a single breeding ground can kill up to 400 females and young, and perhaps eradicate an entire local population.
Fleas are protected, and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disturb them or destroy their nesting grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish collaborator for the Bat Conservation Trust, has urged the public to help in the work.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we simply don’t know how the populations cope.”
