“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safe thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism,” he said.
The state continues to rebuild areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normalcy.
All conditions are now in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they may have left because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war began in 2011.
In addition, six million people still live in the country, in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would welcome aid to rebuild the destroyed country.
But he stressed that conditional aid or assistance from countries that supported the insurgency would not be accepted.
