Algae flowering update: concentrations reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from Florida’s Fisheries and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general decline in redfish concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spotted blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County – suggesting reduced concentrations.
A blossoming of red algae stretches around 210 km along the coast, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
There are spots around 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer locations than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium-sized concentrations at or off the coast of Pinellas County have been reported in the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to high concentrations off the coast or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to high concentrations off the coast of the Colefore in the high concentrations of the County, to medium concentrations in the County Charlo.
Irritation of the airways is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
There have been no reports of airway irritation in Northwest Florida over the past week.
